Intranasal corticosteroids are indicated down to age 2 years. Concerns of reduced growth and adrenal axis suppression have led to differences in the lowest indicated age listed for different steroid molecules (Table 2
). Paired papers published in Pediatrics in 2000 measured a 0.9-cm reduction in annual height gained with intranasal beclomethasone70 and no difference in height with intranasal mometasone.71 The FDA has recommended using the lowest effective dose and monitoring growth in children when prescribing intranasal steroids. Nasal steroids seem to reduce adenoid size and can be considered for moderate adenoid hypertrophy. However, it is unclear how long the nasal steroids have to be maintained to sustain the reduced adenoid size.72 Other allergy medications for children include pseudoephedrine, chromolyn, ipatropium, and montelukast (Table 3
). Montelukast is indicated for perennial AR in children down to age 6 months and may also have a beneficial effect on lower respiratory inflammation.
